# üêû Bug report

This is a bug I've tested in version 8 and version 9 with the way `ng test` bundles rxjs.

### Command (mark with an `x`)

- [x] test

### Is this a regression?

Don't know.

### Description

This is based on [jasmine-marbles#44](https://github.com/synapse-wireless-labs/jasmine-marbles/issues/44). The toHaveSubscriptions function fails because it tries to compare two arrays containing SubscriptionLog objects, but these types have been imported from two different files:

* `node_modules/rxjs/internal/testing/SubscriptionLog.js`
* `node_modules/rxjs/_esm2015/internal/testing/SubscriptionLog.js`

As such, they don't compare equal, and that particular testing function is useless.

Based on what little I've read, this has to do with the way the build optimizer selects its sources.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction
With jasmine-marbles installed, use this test file:

```typescript
import { cold } from 'jasmine-marbles';
import * as rxjs from 'rxjs';
import * as rxop from 'rxjs/operators';

describe('sample', () => {
  fit('demonstrates a problem with build-angular', () => {
    const source = cold(      'a|', { a: { version: '20200203.0' } });
    const HTTP_SUBS =         '^!';
    const expected = cold(    'b|', { b: '20200203.0' });

    const observable = source.pipe(
      rxop.tap(t => console.log(t)),
      rxop.map(v => v.version));

    expect(observable).toBeObservable(expected);
    expect(source).toHaveSubscriptions(HTTP_SUBS);
  });
});

```

## üî• Exception or Error
Jasmine reports:

```
Error: Expected $[0] to be a kind of SubscriptionLog, but was SubscriptionLog({ subscribedFrame: 0, unsubscribedFrame: 10 }).
    at <Jasmine>
    at compare (http://localhost:9876/_karma_webpack_/node_modules/jasmine-marbles/es6/index.js:47:1)
    at <Jasmine>
```


